docs.abstract: President Trump said a group of congresswomen should “go back” to the countries they came from — remarks Democrats roundly condemned as racist and divisive.
docs.snippet: President Trump said a group of congresswomen should “go back” to the countries they came from — remarks Democrats roundly condemned as racist and divisive.
docs.lead_paragraph: Earlier this month, President Trump hurled ugly insults at a group of four Democratic congresswomen of color, saying they hated America and that they should “go back” to the countries they came from, despite the fact that all are United States citizens and all but one was born in the country.

headline.main: How the 2020 Democrats Have Responded to Trump’s Attacks on People of Color

docs.abstract: You may be wondering how the race’s leading liberals differ. Or you may be a progressive voter trying to figure out whom to support. We’re here to help.
docs.snippet: You may be wondering how the race’s leading liberals differ. Or you may be a progressive voter trying to figure out whom to support. We’re here to help.
docs.lead_paragraph: Senators Bernie Sanders of Vermont and Elizabeth Warren of Massachusetts, who will face off on the presidential debate stage for the first time on Tuesday, are often viewed as two sides of the same progressive coin: They are, after all, both liberal populists who want to fundamentally upend the current economic system to help working- and middle-class Americans.

headline.main: How Similar Are Elizabeth Warren and Bernie Sanders, Really?
headline.print_headline: Warren and Sanders, Far From in Lock Step, Show Populism’s Scope

docs.lead_paragraph: As a congressman from a working-class district in Ohio, Tim Ryan has centered his presidential campaign on his ability to appeal to the white working class voters who swung from Barack Obama to Donald Trump — and especially the voters whose livelihoods are threatened by the decline of Midwestern manufacturing.

docs.abstract: “Imagine what would have happened if, God forbid, Barack Obama had been assassinated after becoming the de facto nominee,” Mr. Biden said, evoking the tumult of 1968.
docs.snippet: “Imagine what would have happened if, God forbid, Barack Obama had been assassinated after becoming the de facto nominee,” Mr. Biden said, evoking the tumult of 1968.
docs.lead_paragraph: HANOVER, N.H. — Former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. on Friday took a series of unusual rhetorical detours at the end of a town-hall-style campaign event nominally dedicated to health care, speculating about how a political assassination of Barack Obama might have affected the country in 2008 and recalling that he was accused of being gay because of his support of women’s rights in the 1970s.

headline.main: Joe Biden, Recalling ’68, Asks Audience to Imagine Obama’s Assassination
headline.print_headline: In Analogy to ’68, Biden Imagines if Obama Had Been Killed

byline.original: By Trip Gabriel and Isabella Grullón Paz
